> We're big fans of the ubiquitous "power bowl," but we have to admit: this one's extra special. 
> It's a one-bowl Middle-Eastern feast that's positively bursting with flavor. To start, Israeli 
> couscous is toasted in butter, simmered to chewy perfection, then swirled with baby spinach. 
> On top, there's za'atar-spiced chicken and a dollop of lemony crema.

Melt @butter{2%tablespoon} in a #medium pot{} over medium-high heat. Add @Israeli Couscous{1%cup} and cook, stirring, until browned and toasted, ~{1-2%minutes}. Stir in @Chicken Stock Concentrate{2} and @water{3%cups}. Bring to a boil and cook until al dente, ~{8-10%minutes}. (TIP: If water evaporates before couscous is al dente, add more water, ¼ cup at a time.) Turn off heat.

Meanwhile, wash and dry all produce. Zest @Lemon{2}(zested) until you have 2 tsp; quarter lemons. Pat @Chicken Breast Strips{20%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}; season with @salt{}, @pepper{}, and half the @Za'atar Spice{2%tablespoon}.

Heat @olive oil{4%teaspoon} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Working in batches if necessary, add chicken in a single even layer. Cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and cooked through, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Add @Spinach{5%ounce}, @butter{2%tablespoon}, and juice from 4 lemon wedges to couscous. Cook on low heat, stirring, until spinach has wilted, ~{3-4%minutes}. Turn off heat. Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @Sour Cream{4%tablespoon}, half the lemon zest, a squeeze of lemon juice, and enough @water{} to give mixture a drizzling consistency. (TIP: Start with 1 tsp water and add more as needed.) Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Divide couscous between bowls. Top with chicken. Sprinkle with a pinch of remaining za'atar (we used ¼ tsp) and lemon zest. Drizzle with crema. Serve with any remaining lemon wedges on the side for squeezing over.